Rock Climbing History and Culture through Mountain Project Data

Final Project for INFO 5602, by Mike Flanigan

Introduction

Rock climbing is a long time sport and passion for humans all over the globe. The characters it draws and the stories it has created have built up a rich history in guide books, mountain huts, and campfire stories. However, only in the last two decades has the history, story, and digital data of climbing begun to be accumulated. The defacto database for the digital knowledge of climbing is MountainProject.com. Created in 2005 it provides a community built and grown gathering place for routes, beta (information), pictures, and the general culture of rock climbing to grow.

The objective of the following project was to create a new and engaging way for climbers to visualize the wealth of knowledge and stories that are encoded in the Mountain Project database. A motivating factor for this project was that there isn't a wealth, or even a small sampling, of data visualizations to help tell the story of rock climbing.

Overview data browsing

The following scatter plot shows rock climbs from the Mountain Project database as data points, with the year the route was first climbed on the x axis, and the difficulty of the climb on the y axis. The color of the data point encodes the style of rock climb the route is; Traditional: only removeable gear is used. Sport: permenant gear is is used. Aid: using gear to assist in the climber's ascent. Bouldering: climbing shorter routes without any protective gear.

Hovering over a data point shows thumbnails from the route webpage and some of the relevant information on the route.

The following pie chart also helps give an overview of the rock climbing data from Mountain Project. Each of the four major styles are represented based on their percent of the total rock climbing routes on Mountain Project. Hovering over any of the sections displays a thumbnail that shows a demonstrative photo of that discipline.

Progression and growth of the sport of climbing

Climbing is a progression centric sport. Climbers are usually trying to push their limits, and sometimes even the limits of the sport. The below line plot shows the increase of difficulty of the hardest climbs in each of the disciplines over the years.

As well as progressing in the sports accomplishment, climbing has been growing in popularity of the years and is seeing more main stream media attention. The rapid increase in number of new routes being climbed every year is a great demonstrator of the popularity growth and can be seen below. The color gradient and bar height double encode the number of climbs being added to the Mountain Project database by their year climbed.

Climbing culture

The rock climbing community has long harbored a rich collection of ecclectic, opinionated, counter cultural individuals, all brought together by their shared passion for the outdoors, close comraderie, and love of vertical rock. The following charts show some data on the names of routes created and submitted by climbers from around the world.

The following image shows a word cloud of the most commonly occuring 300 words in route names on Mountain Project. Their frequency of occurance is encoded by their relative size (width, locked aspect ratio) to each other.

The following histogram shows the top 50 words from the above word cloud to give better insight into how frequently these words show up in route names. The number of occurances is again double encoded in height and in color, lending greater visual saliency to the key data attribute.

Along with the prior two figures that show the most commonly occuring route name words, the following image shows the converse. 300 words from route names that are unique in the whole database. These are words that make up and show the creative and unique culture of the climbing community and climbers at large.

Reviews of this vis by some rock climbing enthusiasts:

Jack Marston -- canyon-dwelling sandstone enthusiast -- says:

There exists no such comparable graphical interpretation of such an immense knowledgepool [in the climbing world]... Simply revolutionary.

Scott Guinn -- Aspiring El Cap Liebacker -- says:

The overwhelming number of dots inspires me to want to go out there, risk everything, and become a statistic myself. Really though, very cool and hard to imagine how it could be useful!

Tess Hamilton -- dabbling artist curious about the world of climbing -- says:

As someone who interprets the world visually and knows little about climbing, it is wonderful to see the history and current route information of climbing displayed in an accessible and aesthetic manner. Simply stunning.
